<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-546-344  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 546 344.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  June 11 1990 v218 n24 p11(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cable companies shift 180 degrees. (cable industry willing toaccept form of re-regulation) (News of the Week)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mason, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The cable television and telecommunications industries aredebating the issue of whether telephone companies should beallowed to compete in the cable market.andP;  The cable industryswitched its stance on re-regulation in Jun 1990 to support theregulation of monthly rates for some services and the impositionof controls on activities of large cable operators.andP;  The policychange is an attempt to fend off telephone industry entry into themarket and to end uncertainty over what actions Congress mighttake in response to consumer dissatisfaction with current cablerates and service.andP;  A related amendment by Sen Conrad Burns toallow independent telephone companies into the cable market isbeing justified by the argument that this allowance would speed upavailability of fiber optics in the home.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Telephone companiesCable TVCompetitionRegulationFiber optics.andO;Person:    Burns, Conrad (political activity).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>